      "content": "The p-value of 0.04 doesn't directly tell you the probability that the drug actually works. Instead, it tells you the probability of observing the observed effect (or a more extreme effect) assuming that the null hypothesis is true.\n\nIn other words, the p-value represents the probability of getting a result as extreme or more extreme than the one observed, assuming that the null hypothesis is correct. It doesn't provide any information about the probability of the null hypothesis being false.\n\nThink of it like a coin flip. If you flip a coin 100 times and get heads 55 times, the probability of getting heads 55 times by chance is very low (about 0.04). But that doesn't mean the coin is actually biased towards heads; it just means that the observed result is unlikely to occur by chance.\n\nSimilarly, a p-value of 0.04 doesn't tell you whether the drug actually works or not. It only tells you that the observed effect is unlikely to occur by chance, assuming that the null hypothesis is true. To determine whether the drug actually works, you would need to consider other factors, such as the effect size, the confidence interval, and the clinical significance of the effect.",
